ites like Jobberman, Naijahotjobs, these are useful tools for the business owner who has limited resources to spread around.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When the resumes and credential of candidates who have the qualities the entrepreneur wants are all assembled then there is the issue of interview. The interview process will determine the quality of hire. The Entrepreneur has to come with interview questions that will bring out the skills and attitude of the right candidate.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Before the interview, have a checklist</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul><li>Have questions prepared and a form for noting down the candidates’ response</li><li>Think through sitting arrangement.</li><li>Ensure that you have the resumes/profiles of all shortlisted candidates to be interviewed that day</li><li>Make sure atmosphere is comfortable for everyone involved in the interviewing process</li><li>Don’t pick your calls unless it is an emergency. Don’t keep going out to supervise subordinates or keep candidates waiting endlessly.</li></ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Interview questions should involve those that will not only showcase the candidates’ qualification but his attitude and values also.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When conducting interviews, the entrepreneur should keep quiet 80% of the time and ask open ended questions to allow the candidate express himself. She should also pay special attention to non-verbal language which more often than not says more than words. The efficiency and effectiveness of the recruitment process will determine if the right candidate is hired otherwise the entrepreneur should look forward to going through the process again a few months down the line.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":2} -->\r\n<ol start=\"2\"><li><strong>Compensation and Benefit Strategy</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>The small business owner has to think of innovative ways to be competitive when it comes to paying salaries and other benefits. As paying premium is not going to happen, things like paying for health insurance, running a car pool, crèche, reduction of work hours, payment of commission, addition of certification as an incentive and telecommuting can be introduced. Pension is statutory and compulsory if the organisation has more than five staff irrespective of their employment status, so is employee compensation for companies with staff who do high risk jobs.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":3} -->\r\n<ol start=\"3\"><li><strong>Training Strategy</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Small businesses have limited funds, and high staff turnover, but there is still the need for staff training. Small business owners have to look for inexpensive but effective ways of training their staff. One of this is to ask friends who have experience in different areas to come train your staff pro bono. Another is to give your service in exchange for training. You can also train yourself and pass this knowledge on to your staff.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":4} -->\r\n<ol start=\"4\"><li><strong>Retention Strategy</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Because there is tendency for high staff turnover, SME owners have to be sure that the people working for them know that their work is valued and they have a stake and a future in the business. There should be a succession plan in place, the business owner should run the business transparently, be all inclusive.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":5} -->\r\n<ol start=\"5\"><li><strong>HR Metrics Strategy</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Measurements used to determine the value and effectiveness of HR strategies. “Typically includes such items as cost per hire, turnover rates/costs, training and human capital&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ROI\">ROI</a>, labor /productivity rates and costs, benefit costs per employee. Keep an eye on the bottom-line. Know the labor cost per employee calculator”(Wikipedia). This tells the Management of an organisation how much it spends on each employee from the moment the position is advertised to the day the employee leaves. It takes into consideration, not only the tangible cost such as how much the recruitment firm was paid for the hiring employee, the cost of training, salary, health insurance, leave allowance etc but the intangible such as the cost to the Company when an employee takes medical, maternity, compassionate leave, is absent from work for any other reason, spends the Company’s time on social media etc</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>By calculating the HR metrics, the small business owner will know the cost of hiring, retaining and if it comes to it terminating the appointment of an employee.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>All in all small business owners have to articulate short, mid, and long-term human resources plans that can be updated and improved on as their Companies evolve.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'App\\Models\\Post', 25, 'page', '2021-11-29 05:15:16', '2021-11-29 05:15:16'),
(26, '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Over the years I have discovered there are “4 M’s” to building a successful small business:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Mindset</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Did you know the amount of money you’re earning right now, whether in a job or in a business, is a direct reflection of the value you place on yourself and your services? Your “mindset” about money is what determines how much you earn-much more so than your skills, talents, work ethic or any other criteria.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Many people don’t place a high enough value on their services. They don’t ask to be paid, or even charge, what they’re really worth. Many are even uncomfortable when it comes to asking for money in exchange for services.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>There is a reason this is the first of the four M’s. It’s because you can follow the other 3 M’s, but if you don’t have this first one conquered, you will probably still struggle to make money in your business. Yes, your mindset is THAT important.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How do I know this? I have studied a lot about money mindset over the past 6 years, and I suffered from some major money mindset problems myself in the early years of my business. Once I became aware of my limiting beliefs, and worked to overcome them, my business revenue doubled, and reached the six-figure mark in less than 6 months-after being unable to do so for the previous 6 years.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Multiple Streams</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Very few small business owners can generate six-figure or seven-figure businesses with just one stream of income. Unless you offer a highly specialized service that allows you to command a very high fee, it’s tough to do.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>If you’re currently offering a service, take a look at your business and determine what other income streams you can add, and start taking steps to expand.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>This might mean creating information products or selling other people’s products. It might mean doing group work, such as group coaching or group teleclasses. It might mean adding coaching services or teleclasses to a consulting business.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Be creative and think about new and different ways you can package and offer your expertise. This will help you increase your revenue and serve more people.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Marketing</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Most business owners make the mistake of believing they’re in the business of offering the service they offer. They believe they’re a coach or a consultant, or an accountant or a lawyer. In reality, you need to realize you’re in the business of marketing first and in the business of your profession second.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Look around. I’m sure you can find others who do what you do, who you know are not as qualified or effective as you are, yet have built successful businesses. Why is that? Very likely it’s because they’re great marketers. To be successful in business, you must embrace the idea of marketing and plan to spend at least half of your time marketing your business.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Mentors</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>There are two ways to build a successful business: the hard way and the easy way. Unfortunately many people choose the hard way. They try to figure it all out on their own and they don’t seek out help from others who have already done what they’re trying to do.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Mentors can show you the way, they can tell you what steps to take, they can hold you accountable, they can even help you muster up the courage to do things you’re afraid to do. Mentors don’t always have to be paid. They can also come in many forms. The idea is to seek out the knowledge and expertise you need to successfully build your small business. I have sought mentoring in many forms including good friends, mastermind group members, paid coaches, information products, books and seminars. So before you think you can’t afford a mentor, consider if you can afford NOT to have a mentor.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How long can you wait until your business is profitable? How much frustration can you handle before you give up? These are some important questions to ask yourself before making a snap decision that a mentor is out of your budgetary reach.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>These 4 “M’s” are simple, but very effective when you put them to work in your small busine</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Author: Debbie LaChusa</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Over the years I have discovered there are “4 M’s” to building a successful small business:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Mindset</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Did you know the amount of money you’re earning right now, whether in a job or in a business, is a direct reflection of the value you place on yourself and your services? Your “mindset” about money is what determines how much you earn-much more so than your skills, talents, work ethic or any other criteria.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Many people don’t place a high enough value on their services. They don’t ask to be paid, or even charge, what they’re really worth. Many are even uncomfortable when it comes to asking for money in exchange for services.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>There is a reason this is the first of the four M’s. It’s because you can follow the other 3 M’s, but if you don’t have this first one conquered, you will probably still struggle to make money in your business. Yes, your mindset is THAT important.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How do I know this? I have studied a lot about money mindset over the past 6 years, and I suffered from some major money mindset problems myself in the early years of my business. Once I became aware of my limiting beliefs, and worked to overcome them, my business revenue doubled, and reached the six-figure mark in less than 6 months-after being unable to do so for the previous 6 years.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Multiple Streams</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Very few small business owners can generate six-figure or seven-figure businesses with just one stream of income. Unless you offer a highly specialized service that allows you to command a very high fee, it’s tough to do.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>If you’re currently offering a service, take a look at your business and determine what other income streams you can add, and start taking steps to expand.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>This might mean creating information products or selling other people’s products. It might mean doing group work, such as group coaching or group teleclasses. It might mean adding coaching services or teleclasses to a consulting business.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Be creative and think about new and different ways you can package and offer your expertise. This will help you increase your revenue and serve more people.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Marketing</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Most business owners make the mistake of believing they’re in the business of offering the service they offer. They believe they’re a coach or a consultant, or an accountant or a lawyer. In reality, you need to realize you’re in the business of marketing first and in the business of your profession second.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Look around. I’m sure you can find others who do what you do, who you know are not as qualified or effective as you are, yet have built successful businesses. Why is that? Very likely it’s because they’re great marketers. To be successful in business, you must embrace the idea of marketing and plan to spend at least half of your time marketing your business.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Mentors</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>There are two ways to build a successful business: the hard way and the easy way. Unfortunately many people choose the hard way. They try to figure it all out on their own and they don’t seek out help from others who have already done what they’re trying to do.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Mentors can show you the way, they can tell you what steps to take, they can hold you accountable, they can even help you muster up the courage to do things you’re afraid to do. Mentors don’t always have to be paid. They can also come in many forms. The idea is to seek out the knowledge and expertise you need to successfully build your small business. I have sought mentoring in many forms including good friends, mastermind group members, paid coaches, information products, books and seminars. So before you think you can’t afford a mentor, consider if you can afford NOT to have a mentor.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How long can you wait until your business is profitable? How much frustration can you handle before you give up? These are some important questions to ask yourself before making a snap decision that a mentor is out of your budgetary reach.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>These 4 “M’s” are simple, but very effective when you put them to work in your small busine</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Author: Debbie LaChusa</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'App\\Models\\Post', 26, 'page', '2021-11-29 05:23:25', '2021-11-29 05:23:25'),
(27, '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Treat the interview session like a social process,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the first batch of questions you ask the candidate should help put him at ease</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>as a lot of people will be nervous during such interaction.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Start by giving the candidate an overview of your company.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Introduce yourself and other members of the panel if it is a</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>panel interview.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Asking Questions That Will Let You Know Who the</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Candidate Is.</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>You can start by asking the candidate to tell you about himself.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>You can probe further by talking about his hobbies/interests</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>if any. This will give an insight into who the candidate</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>is. It will enable you know how good his oral communication</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>skills are and will tell you what to expect from him, if you</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>listen very well. For example a candidate who has reading on</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>his list of hobbies and can’t remember the content of the last</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>book he read or even the title is very obviously very economical</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>with the truth.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Tell me about yourself.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What are your strengths and weaknesses?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Where do you see yourself in five or 10 years’ time?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How do you motivate others?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Would you describe yourself as a team player?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you do in your spare time?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Position Requirements</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Review the basic job description and ask the candidate if</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>she/he is able to perform the essential functions of the job.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why are you interested in the job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why are you interested in this industry</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What else can you bring to the company?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you know about the company?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What makes you think that you would be good in this role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What aspects least appeal to you about this role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How do you hope to develop in this role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What changes would you make if given this job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Have you experience of this sort of role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Experience, Knowledge &amp; Skills</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Here you will explore the experience, knowledge and skills</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>that the candidate has acquired. Prepare a sheet of questions</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>that you will ask all candidates and a set of questions specific</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>to each individual candidate. The questions should be linked</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>directly to the requirements stated in the job description.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Probing is a key element in this portion of the interview.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What were the key responsibilities in your last job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How successful do you feel you were?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you rate as your best achievement to date?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is your worst professional failure?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What did you enjoy most about your previous job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you do particularly well?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Can you describe a difficult problem and how you dealt with it?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why do you wish to leave your current job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Ask for details. If the candidate states, she/he</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>was in charge of a project, additional information</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>you may want to probe for the scope of the project,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the actual responsibilities, the number of people involved,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the budget, the outcome, etc.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you see as the most important current trends in theindustry?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you think of the impact of X (recent developments) will be on the industry?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Listen carefully to each response and allow the answer to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>lead into other questions. A rule of thumb to remember during</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>this time is that you should be talking 20% of the time,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the candidate 80%. Use silence effectively. Silence provides</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>time to think. Interviewers who wait out the silence will</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>learn more than those who don’t. A candidate, sensing more</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>information is desired, will often provide more pertinent</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>information. It is important in this portion of interview to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>allow silence.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Goals &amp; Desires</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Here you will assess the candidate’s goals and expectations of</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the job. This is important in determining job satisfaction. An</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>individual seeking rapid advancement or a high profile position</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>may not be satisfied working in the available job. Ask the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>candidate what his salary expectations are.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Scenario/Role Playing:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What qualities are you looking for in the company that you</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>decide to work for?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Who else have you applied to? (This helps to clarify career</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>goals.)</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What are your expectations from the company?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Candidate’s Questions.</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Ask the candidate if she/he has any questions regarding the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>job or any additional information they would like to add</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>about his/her qualifications for the position.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Open the discussion to any questions from the candidate.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Take care in answering these questions no matter how trivial</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>they may seem. They are important to the candidate or the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>questions would not have been asked. If the candidate asks</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>a tough question to which you don’t know the answer, tell</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the candidate you will research the information and get back</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>to her/him. Be sure to follow-up.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>BE PREPARED FOR THESE QUESTIONS</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Can you describe the corporate culture here?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How long have you been here?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you like and not like about working here?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What are you like as a supervisor?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is the most difficult thing about you as a supervisor?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why is this position open?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is the average turnover in this position?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is the biggest difficulty I would face in this job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When do I get a raise?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Do you promote from within?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Closing</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Be sure all the candidate’s questions have been answered and</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>close the interview on a positive note.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Next Steps:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Explain what will happen next in the process. When appropriate,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>tell the candidate that you will be contacting&nbsp;references.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Let the candidate know when you anticipate making</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>a decision and how the candidate will be notified about the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>decision. Be careful not to lead the candidate to believe that</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>she/he has the job. Be gracious, thank the candidate and</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>escort him/her to the door.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Written Impression &amp; Summary</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When the candidate leaves, review your notes and make any</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>additional comments. At the moment, it may seem easy to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>remember everything that took place in the interview. Two</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>or three days later and after several other interviews, it is difficult</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>to distinguish one interview from another.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Evaluate&nbsp;the candidate’s experience and past performance</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>against your job requirements.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Identify each candidate’s strengths and weaknesses?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How will they impact the job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Evaluate indicators of stability and progress.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Will the candidate be compatible with others in the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>department?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Weigh your department’s needs and job requirements</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>with what each candidate is able to offer. Are you able to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>compromise specific requirements for the candidates’</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>strengths in other areas?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong><em>Contributed by Feyikemi Odunuga</em></strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Treat the interview session like a social process,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the first batch of questions you ask the candidate should help put him at ease</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>as a lot of people will be nervous during such interaction.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Start by giving the candidate an overview of your company.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Introduce yourself and other members of the panel if it is a</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>panel interview.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Asking Questions That Will Let You Know Who the</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Candidate Is.</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>You can start by asking the candidate to tell you about himself.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>You can probe further by talking about his hobbies/interests</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>if any. This will give an insight into who the candidate</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>is. It will enable you know how good his oral communication</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>skills are and will tell you what to expect from him, if you</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>listen very well. For example a candidate who has reading on</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>his list of hobbies and can’t remember the content of the last</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>book he read or even the title is very obviously very economical</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>with the truth.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Tell me about yourself.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What are your strengths and weaknesses?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Where do you see yourself in five or 10 years’ time?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How do you motivate others?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Would you describe yourself as a team player?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you do in your spare time?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Position Requirements</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Review the basic job description and ask the candidate if</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>she/he is able to perform the essential functions of the job.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why are you interested in the job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why are you interested in this industry</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What else can you bring to the company?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you know about the company?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What makes you think that you would be good in this role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What aspects least appeal to you about this role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How do you hope to develop in this role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What changes would you make if given this job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Have you experience of this sort of role?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Experience, Knowledge &amp; Skills</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Here you will explore the experience, knowledge and skills</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>that the candidate has acquired. Prepare a sheet of questions</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>that you will ask all candidates and a set of questions specific</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>to each individual candidate. The questions should be linked</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>directly to the requirements stated in the job description.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Probing is a key element in this portion of the interview.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What were the key responsibilities in your last job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How successful do you feel you were?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you rate as your best achievement to date?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is your worst professional failure?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What did you enjoy most about your previous job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you do particularly well?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Can you describe a difficult problem and how you dealt with it?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why do you wish to leave your current job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Ask for details. If the candidate states, she/he</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>was in charge of a project, additional information</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>you may want to probe for the scope of the project,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the actual responsibilities, the number of people involved,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the budget, the outcome, etc.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Sample Questions:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you see as the most important current trends in theindustry?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you think of the impact of X (recent developments) will be on the industry?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Listen carefully to each response and allow the answer to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>lead into other questions. A rule of thumb to remember during</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>this time is that you should be talking 20% of the time,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the candidate 80%. Use silence effectively. Silence provides</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>time to think. Interviewers who wait out the silence will</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>learn more than those who don’t. A candidate, sensing more</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>information is desired, will often provide more pertinent</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>information. It is important in this portion of interview to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>allow silence.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Goals &amp; Desires</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Here you will assess the candidate’s goals and expectations of</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the job. This is important in determining job satisfaction. An</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>individual seeking rapid advancement or a high profile position</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>may not be satisfied working in the available job. Ask the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>candidate what his salary expectations are.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Scenario/Role Playing:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What qualities are you looking for in the company that you</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>decide to work for?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Who else have you applied to? (This helps to clarify career</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>goals.)</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What are your expectations from the company?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Candidate’s Questions.</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Ask the candidate if she/he has any questions regarding the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>job or any additional information they would like to add</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>about his/her qualifications for the position.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Open the discussion to any questions from the candidate.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Take care in answering these questions no matter how trivial</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>they may seem. They are important to the candidate or the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>questions would not have been asked. If the candidate asks</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>a tough question to which you don’t know the answer, tell</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>the candidate you will research the information and get back</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>to her/him. Be sure to follow-up.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>BE PREPARED FOR THESE QUESTIONS</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Can you describe the corporate culture here?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How long have you been here?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What do you like and not like about working here?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What are you like as a supervisor?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is the most difficult thing about you as a supervisor?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Why is this position open?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is the average turnover in this position?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>What is the biggest difficulty I would face in this job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When do I get a raise?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Do you promote from within?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Closing</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Be sure all the candidate’s questions have been answered and</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>close the interview on a positive note.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Next Steps:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Explain what will happen next in the process. When appropriate,</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>tell the candidate that you will be contacting&nbsp;references.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Let the candidate know when you anticipate making</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>a decision and how the candidate will be notified about the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>decision. Be careful not to lead the candidate to believe that</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>she/he has the job. Be gracious, thank the candidate and</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>escort him/her to the door.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Written Impression &amp; Summary</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When the candidate leaves, review your notes and make any</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>additional comments. At the moment, it may seem easy to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>remember everything that took place in the interview. Two</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>or three days later and after several other interviews, it is difficult</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>to distinguish one interview from another.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Evaluate&nbsp;the candidate’s experience and past performance</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>against your job requirements.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Identify each candidate’s strengths and weaknesses?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>How will they impact the job?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Evaluate indicators of stability and progress.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Will the candidate be compatible with others in the</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>department?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Weigh your department’s needs and job requirements</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>with what each candidate is able to offer. Are you able to</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>compromise specific requirements for the candidates’</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>strengths in other areas?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong><em>Contributed by Feyikemi Odunuga</em></strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'App\\Models\\Post', 27, 'page', '2021-11-29 05:33:53', '2021-11-29 05:33:53'),
(28, '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>No matter your resume and talents, if you mess up a job interview you won’t get that position. In today’s tough economy you need every possible edge. As authors of the new book, “I Hate People! Kick Loose from the Overbearing and Underhanded Jerks at Work and Get What you Want Out of Your Job,” we see it as a simple equation: You want to be liked — not hated.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Here are 10 simple things to do that will dramatically increase your chances: from wearing the right expression, to knowing what not to say, to never ever breaking a sweat.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\r\n<ol><li><strong>Don’t be a “smiley face.”</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Excessive smiling in a job interview is seen for what it is — nervousness and a lack of confidence. A smiley-face person exudes phoniness, which will quickly be picked up by the interviewer. Instead be thoughtful and pleasant. Smile when there’s something to smile about. Do a practice run in front of a mirror or friend.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":2} -->\r\n<ol start=\"2\"><li><strong>Don’t be a small-talker.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Your job is to be knowledgeable about the company for which you’re interviewing. Random facts about last night’s episode of “Dancing with the Stars” or your favorite blog will not get you the job. Never feel you have to fill an interview with small talk. Find ways to talk about serious subjects related to the industry or company. Pockets of silence are better than padding an interview with random babble.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":3} -->\r\n<ol start=\"3\"><li><strong>Don’t sweat.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>You can lose a job by wearing an undershirt or simply a little too much clothing. Sweaty palms or beads on your forehead will not impress. You are not applying to be a personal trainer. Sweat will be seen as a sign of weakness and nervousness. Do a practice run with your job interview outfit in front of friends. The job interview is one place you definitely don’t want to be hot.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":4} -->\r\n<ol start=\"4\"><li><strong>Don’t be a road block.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Interviewers are seeking candidates eager to take on challenging projects and jobs. Hesitance and a nay-saying mentality will be as visible as a red tie — and seen as a negative. Practice saying “yes” to questions about your interest in tasks and work that might normally give you pause.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":5} -->\r\n<ol start=\"5\"><li><strong>Don’t be petty.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Asking the location of the lunchroom or meeting room will clue the interviewer into your lack of preparation and initiative. Prepare. Don’t ask questions about routine elements or functions of a company: where stuff is, the size of your cube, and company policy on coffee breaks.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":6} -->\r\n<ol start=\"6\"><li><strong>Don’t be a liar.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Studies show that employees lie frequently in the workplace. Lying won’t get you a job. In a job interview even a slight exaggeration is lying. Don’t. Never stretch your resume or embellish accomplishments. There’s a difference between speaking with a measured confidence and engaging in BS. One lie can ruin your entire interview, and the skilled interviewer will spot the lie and show you the door.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":7} -->\r\n<ol start=\"7\"><li><strong>Don’t be a bad comedian.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Humor tends to be very subjective, and while it may be tempting to lead your interview with a joke you’ve got to be careful about your material. You probably will know nothing about the sensibilities of your interviewer, let alone what makes them laugh. On the other hand, nothing disarms the tension of a job interview like a little laughter, so you can probably score at least a courtesy chuckle mentioning that it’s “perfect weather for a job interview!”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":8} -->\r\n<ol start=\"8\"><li><strong>Don’t be high-maintenance.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>If you start talking about the ideal office temperature, the perfect chair for your tricky back, and how the water cooler needs to be filled with imported mineral water, chances are you’ll be shown a polite smile and the door, regardless of your qualifications. Nobody hiring today is going to be looking for someone who’s going to be finicky about&nbsp;<em>their</em>&nbsp;workspace.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":9} -->\r\n<ol start=\"9\"><li><strong>Don’t be a time-waster.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>At every job interview, the prospective hire is given the chance to ask questions. Make yours intelligent, to the point, and watch the person across the desk for visual cues whether you’ve asked enough. Ask too many questions about off-target matters and you’ll be thought of as someone destined to waste the company’s resources with insignificant and time-wasting matters.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>10<strong>. &nbsp; Don’t be a switchblade.</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Normally the switchblade is thought of as a backstabber, often taking credit for someone else’s work. In an interview setting, the switchblade can’t help but “trash talk” his former employer. If you make it seem like your former workplace was hell on Earth, the person interviewing you might be tempted to call them to find out who was the real devil.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>No matter your resume and talents, if you mess up a job interview you won’t get that position. In today’s tough economy you need every possible edge. As authors of the new book, “I Hate People! Kick Loose from the Overbearing and Underhanded Jerks at Work and Get What you Want Out of Your Job,” we see it as a simple equation: You want to be liked — not hated.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Here are 10 simple things to do that will dramatically increase your chances: from wearing the right expression, to knowing what not to say, to never ever breaking a sweat.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\r\n<ol><li><strong>Don’t be a “smiley face.”</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Excessive smiling in a job interview is seen for what it is — nervousness and a lack of confidence. A smiley-face person exudes phoniness, which will quickly be picked up by the interviewer. Instead be thoughtful and pleasant. Smile when there’s something to smile about. Do a practice run in front of a mirror or friend.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":2} -->\r\n<ol start=\"2\"><li><strong>Don’t be a small-talker.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Your job is to be knowledgeable about the company for which you’re interviewing. Random facts about last night’s episode of “Dancing with the Stars” or your favorite blog will not get you the job. Never feel you have to fill an interview with small talk. Find ways to talk about serious subjects related to the industry or company. Pockets of silence are better than padding an interview with random babble.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":3} -->\r\n<ol start=\"3\"><li><strong>Don’t sweat.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>You can lose a job by wearing an undershirt or simply a little too much clothing. Sweaty palms or beads on your forehead will not impress. You are not applying to be a personal trainer. Sweat will be seen as a sign of weakness and nervousness. Do a practice run with your job interview outfit in front of friends. The job interview is one place you definitely don’t want to be hot.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":4} -->\r\n<ol start=\"4\"><li><strong>Don’t be a road block.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Interviewers are seeking candidates eager to take on challenging projects and jobs. Hesitance and a nay-saying mentality will be as visible as a red tie — and seen as a negative. Practice saying “yes” to questions about your interest in tasks and work that might normally give you pause.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":5} -->\r\n<ol start=\"5\"><li><strong>Don’t be petty.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Asking the location of the lunchroom or meeting room will clue the interviewer into your lack of preparation and initiative. Prepare. Don’t ask questions about routine elements or functions of a company: where stuff is, the size of your cube, and company policy on coffee breaks.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":6} -->\r\n<ol start=\"6\"><li><strong>Don’t be a liar.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Studies show that employees lie frequently in the workplace. Lying won’t get you a job. In a job interview even a slight exaggeration is lying. Don’t. Never stretch your resume or embellish accomplishments. There’s a difference between speaking with a measured confidence and engaging in BS. One lie can ruin your entire interview, and the skilled interviewer will spot the lie and show you the door.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":7} -->\r\n<ol start=\"7\"><li><strong>Don’t be a bad comedian.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Humor tends to be very subjective, and while it may be tempting to lead your interview with a joke you’ve got to be careful about your material. You probably will know nothing about the sensibilities of your interviewer, let alone what makes them laugh. On the other hand, nothing disarms the tension of a job interview like a little laughter, so you can probably score at least a courtesy chuckle mentioning that it’s “perfect weather for a job interview!”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":8} -->\r\n<ol start=\"8\"><li><strong>Don’t be high-maintenance.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>If you start talking about the ideal office temperature, the perfect chair for your tricky back, and how the water cooler needs to be filled with imported mineral water, chances are you’ll be shown a polite smile and the door, regardless of your qualifications. Nobody hiring today is going to be looking for someone who’s going to be finicky about&nbsp;<em>their</em>&nbsp;workspace.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true,\"start\":9} -->\r\n<ol start=\"9\"><li><strong>Don’t be a time-waster.</strong></li></ol>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>At every job interview, the prospective hire is given the chance to ask questions. Make yours intelligent, to the point, and watch the person across the desk for visual cues whether you’ve asked enough. Ask too many questions about off-target matters and you’ll be thought of as someone destined to waste the company’s resources with insignificant and time-wasting matters.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>10<strong>. &nbsp; Don’t be a switchblade.</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Normally the switchblade is thought of as a backstabber, often taking credit for someone else’s work. In an interview setting, the switchblade can’t help but “trash talk” his former employer. If you make it seem like your former workplace was hell on Earth, the person interviewing you might be tempted to call them to find out who was the real devil.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'App\\Models\\Post', 28, 'page', '2021-11-29 05:41:08', '2021-11-29 05:41:08'),
(29, '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>By&nbsp;Kimberly Palmer</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It turns out millionaires are just like everyone else, but they have a lot more money. When asked about their secrets to success, they don’t cite anything magical or rare, but rather the steady application of wise investing strategies, hard work, and, believe it or not, a degree of frugality. Here are 10 secrets of millionaires’ money management:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Start early to avoid financial pitfalls</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Adrian Cartwood, 49, author of the blog&nbsp;<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=Al8zR2W3SV_N22deNBAtfaTFLs8F/SIG=10vmvgaqp/**http%3A/7million7years.com/\">How to Make 7 Million in 7 Years</a>, made his fortune by living frugally while he built his technology-related business. People often get into trouble, he says, by racking up personal debt early on, which acts as a big drag on their earnings. “Learn how to live within your means and how to delay gratification; these are the habits that you need to maintain on the way up, so you can keep your millions when you get there,” he says.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Believe that you can do it</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Before investing in real estate and becoming a millionaire, Alan Corey, author of&nbsp;<em><a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=AgNSsiqpgUe_TBiyuLXmh27FLs8F/SIG=10ukdf8i1/**http%3A/www.alancorey.com/\">A Million Bucks by 30</a></em>, read as many biographies and autobiographies of millionaires as he could find. He says he was searching for a common characteristic that could help him in his own quest. “What I found was they all had an incredible self-belief that they would be financially successful,” he says. Corey says that embracing that level of self-confidence helped him get to the top.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Articulate your vision for success</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Jen Smith, author of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=Ak3l9Ik6NljEwar8.qdd06fFLs8F/SIG=119cks6di/**http%3A/millionairemommynextdoor.com/\">Millionaire Mommy Next Door</a>&nbsp;blog, says that the saying, “I want to be rich,” is too vague. Instead, she recommends imagining what your ideal life as a millionaire will look like. Smith offers this example: “I want to have $2,000,000 invested so that I can live off of the interest. Then I will quit my job so that I can volunteer, travel, learn to play tennis and watercolour, and enjoy picnics at the beach with my family.”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Smith’s vision involved becoming financially-free before becoming a parent. She cut out images from magazines of beautiful places she wanted to visit and people doing fun things and put them near her desk to help her keep that vision in mind.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Insure against life’s risks</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Bankruptcy is often caused by divorce, a death in the family, or a disability that renders someone unable to work. Conversely, protecting against those risks through insurance protects wealth. In The Quiet Millionaire, financial planner Brett Wilder writes that many people either fail to get adequate insurance or pay too much for it because they don’t understand it.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>[For more, read: “<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=Aq706piNAyKjfuDbJZUUJC3FLs8F/SIG=13pno35og/**http%3A/www.usnews.com/articles/business/your-money/2009/03/31/7-killer-insurance-mistakes-youre-probably-making.html\">7 Killer Insurance Mistakes You’re Probably Making</a>.”]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Work hard and you’ll get lucky</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>In his new book, Think Like a Champion, Donald Trump attributes his success to his hard work, which to outsiders often appears to be luck. But Trump says luck only comes from working hard. “If your work pays off, which it most likely will, people might say you’re just lucky. Maybe so, because you’re lucky enough to have the brains to work hard!” he says. That same concept, of course, was advocated by Benjamin Franklin in the 18th century. He said, “The harder I work, the luckier I get.”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Practice smart budgeting</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Smith recommends tracking how much you spend each month, something she does religiously. Every month, she downloads her transactions into a spreadsheet to keep her spending on track. Smith also says that, as prosaic as it sounds, maintaining a good credit score is essential to becoming and staying a millionaire. “A good credit score can save you thousands of dollars over the course of your lifetime,” she says.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Do what you love</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Sure, a career in finance might come with a hefty annual salary, but you probably won’t excel at something you don’t enjoy. That’s why Corey recommends going into the field that you find yourself reading about in your spare time. He asks, “Do you read fashion magazines? Get a job in fashion. Do you read gossip blogs? Get a job in celebrity-based enterprises. Do you read Car &amp; Driver? ESPN.com? Yahoo Pets Forum?” Even if the field doesn’t seem lucrative, there are ways to make it to the top–something that’s more likely to happen if you love it.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>[For more, read: “<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=ApmXV9kqkoYwrSj41EjcLGnFLs8F/SIG=122klelh4/**http%3A/www.usnews.com/sections/business/your-money/index.html\">Juggling Your Money in the Recession</a>.”]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Decide how much money you really want</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>For many people, $1 million won’t be enough. “For most Gen-X and Gen-Yers, retiring with a couple million when they are 65 won’t be anywhere near enough to maintain even an average lifestyle, because that little pup called inflation is constantly nipping at your heels as you try to run towards building your own retirement nest-egg,” says Cartwood. A more reasonable goal might be $3 million– an amount that Cartwood considers the minimum to be a “bare bones millionaire” these days. Consider your ideal lifestyle and what you would like to be able to fund. A mortgage of a certain size? Exotic vacations? College tuition for your children? Having a concrete goal in mind makes it easier to get there, says Cartwood.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Invest against the grain</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Corey recommends making investment decisions based on the exact opposite of what everyone else is doing. Right now, for example, stocks are relatively cheap because so many people have sold off shares, which means anyone buying can get them at a discount to their values from a year ago. Corey’s rule of thumb doesn’t just apply to stocks. “Buy a foreclosed house, fill it up with roommates, and you can get a pretty good passive income,” he suggests.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Live below your means</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Even Eminem, a celebrity and millionaire, scales back his purchases out of concern for frugality. In February, London’s Independent newspaper reported that as Eminem considered buying a $15,000 watch he liked, he started worrying that he should save his money instead. Eminem reportedly said, “I don’t want to run out of money; I want my daughter to be able to go to college.” And so far, at least, Eminem hasn’t fallen victim to the financial challenges so many other stars, from Aretha Franklin to Annie Leibovitz, have faced.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>[For more, read: “<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=AmFNlI017CwjiEdjc0pxVJ3FLs8F/SIG=138opc22c/**http%3A/www.usnews.com/articles/business/your-money/2008/09/16/how-to-go-broke-like-a-rock-star.html\">How to Go Broke Like a Rock Star</a>.”]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>On the same note, Smith says that even though she’s a millionaire, no one would know it–and that’s the point. She recommends saving at least 10 to 25 percent of your income. She also suggests avoiding buying “status” items, such as fancy sports cars or mansions. After all, bling doesn’t make a millionaire–and in fact, too much of it can prevent you from ever becoming one.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>By&nbsp;Kimberly Palmer</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It turns out millionaires are just like everyone else, but they have a lot more money. When asked about their secrets to success, they don’t cite anything magical or rare, but rather the steady application of wise investing strategies, hard work, and, believe it or not, a degree of frugality. Here are 10 secrets of millionaires’ money management:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Start early to avoid financial pitfalls</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Adrian Cartwood, 49, author of the blog&nbsp;<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=Al8zR2W3SV_N22deNBAtfaTFLs8F/SIG=10vmvgaqp/**http%3A/7million7years.com/\">How to Make 7 Million in 7 Years</a>, made his fortune by living frugally while he built his technology-related business. People often get into trouble, he says, by racking up personal debt early on, which acts as a big drag on their earnings. “Learn how to live within your means and how to delay gratification; these are the habits that you need to maintain on the way up, so you can keep your millions when you get there,” he says.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Believe that you can do it</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Before investing in real estate and becoming a millionaire, Alan Corey, author of&nbsp;<em><a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=AgNSsiqpgUe_TBiyuLXmh27FLs8F/SIG=10ukdf8i1/**http%3A/www.alancorey.com/\">A Million Bucks by 30</a></em>, read as many biographies and autobiographies of millionaires as he could find. He says he was searching for a common characteristic that could help him in his own quest. “What I found was they all had an incredible self-belief that they would be financially successful,” he says. Corey says that embracing that level of self-confidence helped him get to the top.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Articulate your vision for success</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Jen Smith, author of the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=Ak3l9Ik6NljEwar8.qdd06fFLs8F/SIG=119cks6di/**http%3A/millionairemommynextdoor.com/\">Millionaire Mommy Next Door</a>&nbsp;blog, says that the saying, “I want to be rich,” is too vague. Instead, she recommends imagining what your ideal life as a millionaire will look like. Smith offers this example: “I want to have $2,000,000 invested so that I can live off of the interest. Then I will quit my job so that I can volunteer, travel, learn to play tennis and watercolour, and enjoy picnics at the beach with my family.”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Smith’s vision involved becoming financially-free before becoming a parent. She cut out images from magazines of beautiful places she wanted to visit and people doing fun things and put them near her desk to help her keep that vision in mind.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Insure against life’s risks</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Bankruptcy is often caused by divorce, a death in the family, or a disability that renders someone unable to work. Conversely, protecting against those risks through insurance protects wealth. In The Quiet Millionaire, financial planner Brett Wilder writes that many people either fail to get adequate insurance or pay too much for it because they don’t understand it.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>[For more, read: “<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=Aq706piNAyKjfuDbJZUUJC3FLs8F/SIG=13pno35og/**http%3A/www.usnews.com/articles/business/your-money/2009/03/31/7-killer-insurance-mistakes-youre-probably-making.html\">7 Killer Insurance Mistakes You’re Probably Making</a>.”]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Work hard and you’ll get lucky</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>In his new book, Think Like a Champion, Donald Trump attributes his success to his hard work, which to outsiders often appears to be luck. But Trump says luck only comes from working hard. “If your work pays off, which it most likely will, people might say you’re just lucky. Maybe so, because you’re lucky enough to have the brains to work hard!” he says. That same concept, of course, was advocated by Benjamin Franklin in the 18th century. He said, “The harder I work, the luckier I get.”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Practice smart budgeting</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Smith recommends tracking how much you spend each month, something she does religiously. Every month, she downloads her transactions into a spreadsheet to keep her spending on track. Smith also says that, as prosaic as it sounds, maintaining a good credit score is essential to becoming and staying a millionaire. “A good credit score can save you thousands of dollars over the course of your lifetime,” she says.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Do what you love</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Sure, a career in finance might come with a hefty annual salary, but you probably won’t excel at something you don’t enjoy. That’s why Corey recommends going into the field that you find yourself reading about in your spare time. He asks, “Do you read fashion magazines? Get a job in fashion. Do you read gossip blogs? Get a job in celebrity-based enterprises. Do you read Car &amp; Driver? ESPN.com? Yahoo Pets Forum?” Even if the field doesn’t seem lucrative, there are ways to make it to the top–something that’s more likely to happen if you love it.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>[For more, read: “<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=ApmXV9kqkoYwrSj41EjcLGnFLs8F/SIG=122klelh4/**http%3A/www.usnews.com/sections/business/your-money/index.html\">Juggling Your Money in the Recession</a>.”]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Decide how much money you really want</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>For many people, $1 million won’t be enough. “For most Gen-X and Gen-Yers, retiring with a couple million when they are 65 won’t be anywhere near enough to maintain even an average lifestyle, because that little pup called inflation is constantly nipping at your heels as you try to run towards building your own retirement nest-egg,” says Cartwood. A more reasonable goal might be $3 million– an amount that Cartwood considers the minimum to be a “bare bones millionaire” these days. Consider your ideal lifestyle and what you would like to be able to fund. A mortgage of a certain size? Exotic vacations? College tuition for your children? Having a concrete goal in mind makes it easier to get there, says Cartwood.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Invest against the grain</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Corey recommends making investment decisions based on the exact opposite of what everyone else is doing. Right now, for example, stocks are relatively cheap because so many people have sold off shares, which means anyone buying can get them at a discount to their values from a year ago. Corey’s rule of thumb doesn’t just apply to stocks. “Buy a foreclosed house, fill it up with roommates, and you can get a pretty good passive income,” he suggests.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Live below your means</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Even Eminem, a celebrity and millionaire, scales back his purchases out of concern for frugality. In February, London’s Independent newspaper reported that as Eminem considered buying a $15,000 watch he liked, he started worrying that he should save his money instead. Eminem reportedly said, “I don’t want to run out of money; I want my daughter to be able to go to college.” And so far, at least, Eminem hasn’t fallen victim to the financial challenges so many other stars, from Aretha Franklin to Annie Leibovitz, have faced.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>[For more, read: “<a href=\"http://us.lrd.yahoo.com/_ylt=AmFNlI017CwjiEdjc0pxVJ3FLs8F/SIG=138opc22c/**http%3A/www.usnews.com/articles/business/your-money/2008/09/16/how-to-go-broke-like-a-rock-star.html\">How to Go Broke Like a Rock Star</a>.”]</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>On the same note, Smith says that even though she’s a millionaire, no one would know it–and that’s the point. She recommends saving at least 10 to 25 percent of your income. She also suggests avoiding buying “status” items, such as fancy sports cars or mansions. After all, bling doesn’t make a millionaire–and in fact, too much of it can prevent you from ever becoming one.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'App\\Models\\Post', 29, 'page', '2021-11-29 05:50:54', '2021-11-29 06:29:32'),
(30, '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>According to Wikipedia, a Performance Appraisal (PA) is a systematic and periodic process that assesses an individual employee’s job performance and productivity in relation to certain pre-established criteria and organizational objectives. Other aspects of individual employees are considered as well, such as&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organizational_citizenship_behavior\">organizational citizenship behaviour</a>, accomplishments, potential for future improvement, strengths and weaknesses, e.t.c. To collect PA data, there are three main methods: objective production, personnel, and judgemental evaluation. Judgemental evaluations are the most commonly used with a large variety of evaluation methods. &nbsp;A PA is typically conducted annually.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Performance management however is the process of creating a work environment or setting in which people are enabled to perform to the best of their abilities. Performance management begins when you determine that a job function is needed. It ends when an employee leaves your organization. When developing the system, ensure there is a clear job description for the position that highlights the purpose of the job, the duties and responsibilities.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Job Descriptions should clearly describe the employee’s current duties and performance expectations. Position descriptions should be specific, clearly defining the job function, required skills, deadlines, and goals, and should delineate expectations for the employee’s relations with peers and the customers. Job descriptions should be kept current. Once you have job descriptions in place; you need to establish performance standards that describe what constitutes below-average, average, above average performance. Start by thinking about the best and the worst case scenarios until you reach realistic standards for measuring performance after which you select appropriate people with the right hiring process.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When the person has been employed, the Supervisor should have a meeting where the requirements of the job and what it is to accomplish is discussed. At this meeting performance standards, outcomes, and measures are discussed and agreed on. The Supervisor should define the priority of each job responsibility and goal. He should define performance standards for key components of the job and also discuss performance goals with measurable outcomes with the employee.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Performance management will take into consideration the design of effective compensation and recognition systems that reward people for their contributions. It provides promotional/career development opportunities for staff.&nbsp;The employee is also to be oriented properly and effectively, educated, trained and empowered to do the job.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It is usually suggested that Performance Appraisal be done every six months, for effective feedback. Midway into this process, that is quarterly, performance development discussions should be held. The employee can also call for meetings to ask for help in meeting his goals or ask for more training or tools to be provided. Hold interim discussions and provide feedback about employee performance, preferably daily, summarized and discussed, at least, quarterly. (Provide positive and constructive feedback.) All meetings and agreements should be documented and signed by both parties always.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Supervisors should set SMART (Specific, Measurable, Agree-upon, Realistic and Time bound) goals.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It is extremely important that Supervisors should maintain a record of performance through critical incident reports. (Jot notes about contributions or problems throughout the quarter, in an employee file.) Provide the opportunity for broader feedback. Use a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://humanresources.about.com/od/360feedback/a/360feedback.htm\">360 degree performance feedback system</a>&nbsp;that incorporates feedback from the employee’s peers, customers, and people who may report to him.&nbsp;If an employee at the end of the appraisal cycle fails to meet one of the set criteria, he is regarded as having failed to meet all and should be placed on a Performance Improvement Plan. This is when the Supervisor develops and administers a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://humanresources.about.com/od/performancemanagement/a/PIP.htm\">coaching and improvement plan</a>.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Where an employee decides to leave the Company the supervisor should conduct an exit interview to understand&nbsp;<strong>WHY</strong>&nbsp;valued employees leave the organization.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Organisations especially small businesses are encouraged to take the path of Performance Management because it is more objective and can ensure that all that is required for the employee to perform optimally is done. Unlike the Appraisal only method, which can be subjective, easy to disprove and claims of bias can be made against supervisors.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Small business owners should ensure that their Company’s appraisal system is a two-way system not one-way.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>According to Wikipedia, a Performance Appraisal (PA) is a systematic and periodic process that assesses an individual employee’s job performance and productivity in relation to certain pre-established criteria and organizational objectives. Other aspects of individual employees are considered as well, such as&nbsp;<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organizational_citizenship_behavior\">organizational citizenship behaviour</a>, accomplishments, potential for future improvement, strengths and weaknesses, e.t.c. To collect PA data, there are three main methods: objective production, personnel, and judgemental evaluation. Judgemental evaluations are the most commonly used with a large variety of evaluation methods. &nbsp;A PA is typically conducted annually.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Performance management however is the process of creating a work environment or setting in which people are enabled to perform to the best of their abilities. Performance management begins when you determine that a job function is needed. It ends when an employee leaves your organization. When developing the system, ensure there is a clear job description for the position that highlights the purpose of the job, the duties and responsibilities.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Job Descriptions should clearly describe the employee’s current duties and performance expectations. Position descriptions should be specific, clearly defining the job function, required skills, deadlines, and goals, and should delineate expectations for the employee’s relations with peers and the customers. Job descriptions should be kept current. Once you have job descriptions in place; you need to establish performance standards that describe what constitutes below-average, average, above average performance. Start by thinking about the best and the worst case scenarios until you reach realistic standards for measuring performance after which you select appropriate people with the right hiring process.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>When the person has been employed, the Supervisor should have a meeting where the requirements of the job and what it is to accomplish is discussed. At this meeting performance standards, outcomes, and measures are discussed and agreed on. The Supervisor should define the priority of each job responsibility and goal. He should define performance standards for key components of the job and also discuss performance goals with measurable outcomes with the employee.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Performance management will take into consideration the design of effective compensation and recognition systems that reward people for their contributions. It provides promotional/career development opportunities for staff.&nbsp;The employee is also to be oriented properly and effectively, educated, trained and empowered to do the job.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It is usually suggested that Performance Appraisal be done every six months, for effective feedback. Midway into this process, that is quarterly, performance development discussions should be held. The employee can also call for meetings to ask for help in meeting his goals or ask for more training or tools to be provided. Hold interim discussions and provide feedback about employee performance, preferably daily, summarized and discussed, at least, quarterly. (Provide positive and constructive feedback.) All meetings and agreements should be documented and signed by both parties always.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Supervisors should set SMART (Specific, Measurable, Agree-upon, Realistic and Time bound) goals.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It is extremely important that Supervisors should maintain a record of performance through critical incident reports. (Jot notes about contributions or problems throughout the quarter, in an employee file.) Provide the opportunity for broader feedback. Use a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://humanresources.about.com/od/360feedback/a/360feedback.htm\">360 degree performance feedback system</a>&nbsp;that incorporates feedback from the employee’s peers, customers, and people who may report to him.&nbsp;If an employee at the end of the appraisal cycle fails to meet one of the set criteria, he is regarded as having failed to meet all and should be placed on a Performance Improvement Plan. This is when the Supervisor develops and administers a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://humanresources.about.com/od/performancemanagement/a/PIP.htm\">coaching and improvement plan</a>.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Where an employee decides to leave the Company the supervisor should conduct an exit interview to understand&nbsp;<strong>WHY</strong>&nbsp;valued employees leave the organization.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Organisations especially small businesses are encouraged to take the path of Performance Management because it is more objective and can ensure that all that is required for the employee to perform optimally is done. Unlike the Appraisal only method, which can be subjective, easy to disprove and claims of bias can be made against supervisors.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Small business owners should ensure that their Company’s appraisal system is a two-way system not one-way.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'App\\Models\\Post', 30, 'page', '2021-11-29 05:54:48', '2021-11-29 05:54:48');
